article.description:
Chauncey Billups scored 28 points,
including the last eight in the second overtime Sunday night, to
lead the Detroit Pistons to a 110-107 victory over the Memphis
Grizzlies.
article.headline: Pistons tied with idle Nets for first place  in East
article.linkText: Billups, Pistons clinch Central title with latest OT win
article.story:
MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- The Detroit Pistons had to put in some extra work before clinching the Central Division title.
Billups

And now, they want to secure the top spot in the Eastern Conference. Chauncey Billups scored 28 points, including the last eight in the second overtime Sunday night, to lead the Pistons to a 110-107 victory over the Memphis Grizzlies. Coupled with the Indiana Pacers' 107-98 loss to the Milwaukee Bucks earlier in the day, the Pistons hold a three-game lead in the division with two games left. "That's what we set out to do when we sat down in training camp,'' Billups said. "We said we wanted to win the Central Division and have a chance to win the East. We're right there. We're in control of our own destiny now.'' Detroit, which is 8-0 in overtime games, is tied with idle New Jersey for the top playoff spot in the East. "It's an accomplishment to win a division title for the second year in a row,'' Detroit coach Rick Carlisle said. Corliss Williamson made a key steal from Memphis's Pau Gasol with about 25 seconds left, setting up two free throws by Billups with 17 seconds remaining that accounted for the final margin. "The play was there all night,'' Williamson said. "(Gasol) had been doing a great job of getting to the middle. It was the opportune time to do it, and I was able to get my hand on the ball.'' Memphis' Shane Battier tracked down a loose ball in the backcourt with about 2 seconds left, but missed a shot from midcourt at the buzzer. Billups also had 10 rebounds and six assists as six Pistons finished in double figures, including three who had double-doubles. Richard Hamilton added 18 points, while Williamson had 14. Jon Barry, who led a fourth-quarter comeback for Detroit, scored 13 as did Mehmet Okur, who grabbed 12 rebounds. Clifford Robinson had 10 points and 10 rebounds. Gasol led Memphis with 24 points, while Battier finished with 22. Stromile Swift had 21 before fouling out in the first overtime, while Mike Batiste added 14 off the bench. Gasol made the second of two free throws with 26.9 seconds left in regulation to tie it at 93 and send it to overtime. Billups missed a stumbling drive to the basket as time expired in regulation. Okur's 3-pointer with 1:10 left in the first overtime tied it at 100, sending it to the second extra period. Barry scored 12 fourth-quarter points, including seven of Detroit's 10 in the final 2:39, to help erase a 10-point Memphis lead, at one point giving Detroit a pair of one-point leads in the final two minutes. "I thought Barry's contribution was key,'' Carlisle said. "He hit some shots, got to the rim and defensively was solid.'' Memphis coach Hubie Brown saw his team squander a 10-point lead in the fourth to send the game into overtime. Brown said the key was Detroit connecting on all four of its 3-pointers in the period, while Memphis missed four of its seven free throws. "We had the game won in the fourth quarter,'' Brown said before citing the Pistons' 3-point shooting. "We missed four critical foul shots, and we had critical turnovers in the fourth and in the overtime. You can't turn it over against a team that is fighting for the top spot in the East.'' Memphis used the energy and defensive pressure from its reserves to build a 10-point first half lead and take a 50-46 advantage at intermission. Swift had 10 points, missing only one of his five shots, but the reserves built the lead with the help of a couple of 3-pointers by Battier in the second quarter. But Detroit fought back in the fourth quarter and took over in the late stages of the second overtime. "We feel like the type of basketball we play is more suited for the playoffs and overtime because its king of a slow, grinding out-type of pace,'' Williamson said. "When we get to overtime, we seem to have a lot of confidence.'' Game notes
Pistons F/C Ben Wallace missed his fourth game with a sprained left MCL, and is expected to miss two weeks. Billups said they are ready for the league's leading rebounder and shot-blocker to return. "I asked him (Saturday) 'When is your vacation over?''' ... Memphis has not beaten the Pistons since moving from Vancouver before last season, losing four straight. Detroit leads the series 11-3. ... Gasol finished with nine rebounds, snapping his streak of four straight double-doubles. ... Detroit is 18-0 when scoring more than 100 points. ... Jason Williams, who had scored 38 points in the last two games, was held to six points on 2-of-9 from the field.
